"""
MKT Christ Commentary — John chapter 11
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-john-11-11.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text for quoting)
- data/parallels/john.json (absorbed: Dan 9:25-26 on v51 — Caiaphas prophecy)
- data/translation/glossary-greek.json (anastasis, zōē, embrimaomai, klaíō)

Key decisions in this range:
- Author referred to as "the Evangelist"; Jesus as "Jesus" or "the Son" or "Christ"
- v11 "fallen asleep": classified as revelation of God — Jesus' sovereign reframing of death
- v25-26 "I am the resurrection and the life": classified as direct revelation — the fifth Johannine
  "I am" with predicate; the most comprehensive life-claim in the Gospel; the source, not merely
  the agent, of resurrection
- v27 Martha's confession: classified as direct — the fullest pre-resurrection confession in John,
  paralleling but preceding Thomas's post-resurrection confession (20:28)
- v35 "Jesus wept": classified as revelation of God through incarnation — genuine grief; not
  performance; connects to Isa 53:3 (man of sorrows, acquainted with grief)
- v40 "glory of God": classified as revelation of God — faith before sign; the consistent Johannine
  epistemology
- v43-44 "Lazarus, come out!": classified as direct revelation — the creative command; Ezek 37 enacted;
  the seventh and greatest sign of the Book of Signs; the most direct preview of the resurrection
- v50-52 Caiaphas's prophecy: classified as direct — the Evangelist explicitly marks it as prophecy;
  Dan 9:25-26 (the anointed one cut off) absorbed from parallels; "scattered children of God" echoes
  Isa 49:6 and Ezek 34:12-16
- v55-57 Passover approaching: classified as shadow — the gathering of pilgrims and the approaching
  Passover frames Lazarus's resurrection as pointing toward the greater Passover event
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JOHN = {
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>A theme: Lazarus of Bethany is introduced as a named individual whose death and resurrection will be the climactic sign of the Book of Signs. The Evangelist has narrated signs progressively — water to wine (ch 2), healing of the official\'s son (ch 4), the paralyzed man (ch 5), feeding five thousand (ch 6), healing of the blind man (ch 9) — each escalating. The seventh sign will be the raising of the dead. The narrative of Lazarus is the lens through which the reader is to understand the resurrection of Christ that follows.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: the parenthetical identification of Mary as the one who anointed Jesus (an event the Evangelist will narrate in ch 12) connects the Lazarus narrative to the anointing that prepares Jesus for his own burial. The two events bracket each other: the raising of Lazarus points forward to Christ\'s death, and the anointing for burial points forward to his resurrection. The Evangelist\'s literary architecture is deliberate — Lazarus\'s death and resurrection are the theological lens for understanding what is about to happen to Jesus.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: the sisters\' message — "Lord, the one you love is sick" — is the most minimal of prayers. They do not prescribe what Jesus should do; they simply report the situation to the one who loves. The appeal to Jesus\' love is the ground of the request, not its content. This is the posture the NT consistently models: bringing the situation to Christ\'s attention without dictating the response. The one who loves will determine the appropriate action, which will be greater than what the sisters imagined.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A direct revelation: "This sickness will not end in death. No, it is for God\'s glory so that God\'s Son may be glorified through it." The Evangelist uses the cross-glorification language that runs through John — the "hour" of glorification is the hour of the cross and resurrection (12:23–28; 17:1). Lazarus\'s death is not the end but the occasion for the greatest sign. The pattern is already established: death enters the scene, and the Son\'s glory is disclosed through his mastery of it. The raising of Lazarus is the penultimate act; the crucifixion and resurrection are the ultimate.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jesus loved Martha and her sister and Lazarus." The threefold naming emphasizes the personal character of this love. The word is <em>agapaō</em> — the covenant love that the Evangelist has attributed to the Father (3:16) and to Christ throughout the Gospel. His decision to delay (v6) is not lack of care but a deeper care — the one who loves them will do for them what they cannot imagine requesting. The delay that seems like indifference is the prelude to the greatest gift.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: "when he heard that Lazarus was sick, he stayed where he was two more days." The two-day delay is governed by divine timing, not human urgency. The Evangelist has consistently presented Christ as acting on the Father\'s schedule rather than human pressure (2:4 — "my hour has not yet come"; 7:6 — "the right time for me has not yet come"). The delay is not cruelty but sovereignty — by the time Jesus arrives, Lazarus will have been four days in the tomb (v17), beyond any possibility of doubt about the reality of his death.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A revelation of God: "Let us go back to Judea." The decision to return to the place of danger is the decision of the one who moves toward the cross rather than away from it. The Evangelist has already narrated the threats against Jesus in Jerusalem (5:18; 7:1; 8:59; 10:31–33). To return now is to accept the escalating risk. The one who goes to raise Lazarus is the one who goes to his own death — and both journeys are part of the same mission.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme: the disciples\' objection — "the Jews there were trying to stone you" — is the voice of self-preservation, reasonable by every human calculation. The Evangelist presents it as a foil to Christ\'s deliberate willingness to go into danger. The disciples fear death; Jesus is going to defeat it. Their warning is honest and theologically significant: they have understood that Jerusalem is dangerous; they have not yet understood that Jesus is going precisely because the hour of his self-giving is approaching.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "Are there not twelve hours of daylight? Anyone who walks in the daytime will not stumble, for they see by this world\'s light." Christ operates within the Father\'s appointed window — the "day" of his mission before the "night" of the cross (cf. 9:4: "night is coming when no one can work"). He is not reckless; he is confident that within the Father\'s appointed time, no threat can end his life prematurely. The hour of his death is not determined by his enemies\' attempts but by the Father\'s schedule.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: "it is when a person walks at night that they stumble, for they have no light." The light/darkness metaphor that opened the Gospel (1:4–5) returns here applied to the mission. Those who act outside the Father\'s will, in the darkness of self-determination, stumble. Christ walks in the light of perfect alignment with the Father\'s will and therefore cannot stumble — even in Jerusalem, even approaching the cross. The light he is (1:4–9) is what guides him.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "Our friend Lazarus has fallen asleep; but I am going there to wake him up." The language of sleep for death is common in Jewish usage (and in the NT: 1 Cor 15:51; 1 Thess 4:14), but Jesus uses it with authority — not merely as a euphemism but as a sovereign reframing. For the one who is "the resurrection and the life" (v25), death is sleep from which he awakens the sleeper. The claim embedded in "I am going to wake him up" is the claim of one for whom death is not the final word but a temporary state subject to his command.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: the disciples\' misunderstanding — "if he sleeps, he will get better" — is the Evangelist\'s characteristic device of literal-level reception. They receive "sleep" as a good sign, missing the depth of what Jesus means. The misunderstanding sets up the plain statement of v14 ("Lazarus is dead") and the full revelation of what Jesus is going to do. The disciples are at the level of natural expectation; Jesus is operating at the level of eschatological action.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "Jesus had been speaking of his death, but his disciples thought he meant natural sleep." The narrator\'s explanation is the Evangelist\'s consistent practice: the two levels of meaning in Jesus\' words are visible to the reader even when hidden from the characters. The disciples operate at the natural level; Jesus speaks at the level of divine sovereignty over death. The gap between the two registers — which the reader has been educated to navigate throughout John — is here made explicit.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: "Lazarus is dead" — spoken plainly, without euphemism now, to correct the misunderstanding. The plainness of the statement is itself significant: Jesus does not soften the reality of Lazarus\'s death. The sign he is about to perform will not sidestep death but will confront it directly. The resurrection the Evangelist is narrating is not a near-death recovery but the reversal of actual death, and Jesus states the reality of the death before he reverses it.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A revelation of God: "for your sake I am glad I was not there, so that you may believe." The delay that seemed like abandonment is now revealed as gift — the disciples\' faith will be strengthened by seeing a greater work than they could have asked for if Jesus had arrived earlier. The Evangelist\'s consistent pedagogical pattern: the temporary absence or apparent inaction of Jesus creates the space for a greater disclosure of who he is. This is the Christological logic of the passion itself — the apparent abandonment of the cross is the greatest gift.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: Thomas\'s "Let us also go, that we may die with him" is the most honest statement of courage in the disciples\' company — and the most ironic. He is willing to die with Lazarus and with Jesus. He does not understand yet that the one he follows will die for Thomas, not with him; or that the death toward which they are walking will be reversed. Thomas\'s dark courage will become the faith of 20:28 ("my Lord and my God") — but only after the resurrection transforms his willingness to die into understanding of who it is that conquers death.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: "Lazarus had already been in the tomb for four days." The four days are the Evangelist\'s sign that Lazarus is genuinely dead — not in a coma, not temporarily insensible. Jewish tradition held that the soul hovered near the body for three days but departed on the fourth; by day four, decomposition was assumed to have begun (v39: "by this time there is a bad odor"). The Evangelist is ensuring that no reader can reduce what follows to a near-death recovery. This is a confrontation with actual death.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme: Bethany\'s proximity to Jerusalem — "less than two miles" — places the raising of Lazarus within reach of the capital and its authorities. It also ensures that the sign will be witnessed by many Jews from Jerusalem (v19, v45–46), increasing both its impact and the danger to Jesus. The Evangelist\'s geography is never incidental; Jerusalem\'s nearness is the reason the sign will trigger the Sanhedrin\'s final decision against Jesus (vv47–53).</p>',
    "19": '<p>A theme: the many Jews who had come to comfort the sisters provide the witnesses necessary for the sign to function as testimony. The presence of the Jerusalem community — some of whom will go to the Pharisees (v46) — means that the raising of Lazarus cannot be dismissed as a private event or misrepresented as a rumor. The Evangelist has staged the scene so that the sign is performed in front of credible, motivated, diverse witnesses, some of whom will respond in faith and some in hostility.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: Martha\'s going out to meet Jesus while Mary stays home reflects two postures before grief that both prove to be postures before Christ. Martha\'s active meeting leads to the great dialogue of vv21–27; Mary\'s staying leads to the emotional encounter of vv32–36. Both sisters reach the same point of faith (v27, 45); they arrive by different paths. The Evangelist honors both approaches to Christ: the searching mind and the grieving heart each find him where they are.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A revelation of God: "Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died" — Martha\'s reproach is simultaneously a statement of faith and an expression of bewilderment. She believes Jesus could have prevented the death. She does not yet believe he can reverse it (v39 shows she hesitates even after v25). Her cry is the honest prayer of those who have experienced divine delay as divine absence. Jesus does not correct the reproach but engages it — the grief is real, the faith is real, and the answer that follows exceeds both.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A revelation of God: "But I know that even now God will give you whatever you ask." Martha\'s "even now" is remarkable — she has not abandoned hope even in the face of four-day death. She cannot fully articulate what she is hoping for (her v24 response suggests she interprets Jesus\' next statement in future/eschatological terms), but she has opened the door. The Evangelist shows a faith that outstrips its own understanding — she believes in a "now" intervention without knowing what form it will take.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "Your brother will rise again." Jesus\' statement is deliberately ambiguous — it can be heard as the conventional eschatological promise, which Martha immediately assigns to the last day (v24), or as the immediate announcement of what is about to happen. The Evangelist\'s double-meaning device operates here at maximum force: the statement is literally true on both levels. What happens to Lazarus in vv43–44 is both a sign of what happens at the last day and the act of the one who makes both possible.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A theme: Martha\'s answer — "I know he will rise again in the resurrection at the last day" — is theologically correct and existentially insufficient. She holds the Pharisaic doctrine of bodily resurrection (shared by many Jews but not the Sadducees). But "the last day" is in the future; her grief is in the present. Christ\'s response will relocate the power of resurrection from the last day to the present person standing before her. The correct theology needs to be inhabited by the living presence of the one who holds the power it describes.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A direct revelation — the fifth of the great "I am" statements with a predicate: "I am the resurrection and the life." Jesus does not say "I will cause the resurrection" or "I will be present at the resurrection." He says he <em>is</em> the resurrection — the principle, the power, the source. The resurrection is not a future event that will occur independently of him; it is grounded in and inseparable from his own person. Wherever he is, the resurrection-life is present. This is the Christological claim that the raising of Lazarus will enact and that the resurrection of Christ will verify.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation: "whoever lives by believing in me will never die." The two statements of vv25–26 address two aspects of the resurrection-life: physical death will be reversed ("even though they die, they will live"), and for the believer in the present age, the spiritual death that awaits has already been crossed over (5:24). "Will never die" (<em>ou mē apothanē eis ton aiōna</em>) is the strong Greek double-negative — absolute exclusion of eternal death for the one who believes. The life Christ gives is indestructible because it originates in the one who cannot be destroyed.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct revelation: Martha\'s confession — "Yes, Lord, I believe that you are the Messiah, the Son of God, who is to come into the world" — is the fullest pre-resurrection confession in the Gospel, paralleling and anticipating Thomas\'s post-resurrection "my Lord and my God" (20:28). She names the three central titles: Messiah (the anointed king of Israel\'s expectation), Son of God (the divine sonship Jesus has been claiming throughout John), and the one who is to come into the world (the eschatological figure the Baptist pointed to, 1:15; cf. Ps 118:26). The Evangelist positions this confession at the center of the Lazarus narrative as its theological ground.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: Martha goes to call her sister privately — "the Teacher is here, and is asking for you." The word "Teacher" (<em>didaskalos</em>) is the term of respect and trust; Martha uses it in the context of the greatest claim (v25) she has just received. The private summons reflects both the intimacy of the relationship with Jesus and the discretion of someone in a grief-filled house full of mourners. The detail is human and accurate; the Evangelist narrates the approach of Christ to each sister with care for their different natures.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A revelation of God: Mary "got up quickly and went to him" — the urgency of her movement contrasts with her sitting still while the mourners remained (v20, v31). Her quick response mirrors the urgency of her grief and her faith: the one she has been waiting for has sent for her. The movement toward Christ — urgent, physical, direct — is the Evangelist\'s consistent image of what genuine faith looks like in action. The mourners following her (v31) will become additional witnesses to what follows.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A theme: Jesus has not yet entered the village but waits at the meeting point where Martha found him. The location outside the village creates a liminal space — between the ordinary world of the village and the encounter with the one who is about to do something that will change everything. The Evangelist stages the scene carefully: the movement of the mourners toward this threshold is the movement toward the sign.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A theme: the Jews follow Mary, assuming she is going to the tomb to mourn. Their assumption is the last thing they know — they are operating within the framework of ordinary death and ordinary grief. They are about to witness something that will shatter that framework. The Evangelist presents the mourners as typical representatives of the human condition before Christ: sincere, sympathetic, and entirely unprepared for what is about to happen.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: Mary falls at Jesus\' feet — the posture of worship and urgent appeal — and says the same thing Martha said (v21): "Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died." The identical words from both sisters reflect the shared grief of the household; the different approach (prostration vs. direct address) reflects their different natures. Both reach the same point: the one they love has arrived too late, or so they believe. Jesus\' response to Mary\'s tears will be the most humanly vivid verse in the chapter.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: "he was deeply moved in spirit and troubled." The Greek <em>enebrimēsato tō pneumati</em> is a strong term — it denotes a deep inward agitation, even a kind of righteous indignation. Some interpreters read it as anger at the reign of death and the grief it produces; others as the most intense form of sympathetic grief. Both are present: Christ is genuinely troubled by what he sees, and his trouble is the trouble of the one who did not create the world for death. The Incarnation means he experiences the consequences of the Fall from the inside.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "Where have you laid him?" Jesus asks, not because he does not know, but because the question draws him into the community\'s grief and locates the sign at the specific place of death. The divine omniscience (2:25; 4:17–18) does not require the question; the pastoral engagement with the mourning community does. The one who is about to command Lazarus out of the tomb first asks where the tomb is — the all-knowing Son entering the situation of those who know and grieve.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God through incarnation: "Jesus wept." The shortest verse in the Gospel contains the deepest Christological statement in the chapter about the Incarnation. The Son of God weeps. His tears are genuine — not performance, not calculation. He who is "the resurrection and the life" weeps at a tomb, because he is also the fully human Son who loves Lazarus and feels the weight of the grief surrounding him. Isaiah 53:3 calls the Servant "a man of sorrows, acquainted with grief." This verse enacts that description. The tears of Christ are the tears of God entering human loss.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A revelation of God: "See how he loved him!" — the Jews\' reading is correct. Jesus weeps because he loves Lazarus. The Evangelist has already named this love explicitly (v5). The mourners\' observation validates the genuineness of his tears: this is not a sign-prelude but an expression of the covenant love that prompted the journey and the sign. The same love that moves him to weep moves him to raise — the tears and the command are two expressions of the same divine-human love.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A revelation of God: "Could not he who opened the eyes of the blind man have kept this man from dying?" The question is the honest expression of the expectation that power should prevent suffering. It is also the question that misunderstands the economy of divine love: Christ could have prevented the death; he chose not to, so that something greater could occur. The same question will be asked at the cross: "He saved others; let him save himself" (Luke 23:35). In both cases the answer is that the Son\'s power is expressed not in avoiding death but in overcoming it.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A revelation of God: "once more deeply moved" — the second use of <em>embrimaomai</em> (v33) intensifies what has been building. Jesus arrives at the tomb with the emotional and spiritual intensity of one about to confront the last enemy (1 Cor 15:26 — "the last enemy to be destroyed is death"). The cave with its stone is the image of sealed finality — death enclosed, inaccessible. He is about to speak into that finality. The emotion is not sentimentality but the righteous indignation of the one who made the world and will not yield it to death.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A revelation of God: Martha\'s hesitation — "by this time there is a bad odor, for he has been there four days" — is the Evangelist\'s confirmation that she has not yet absorbed what Jesus told her in vv25–26. Her faith in the abstract resurrection of the last day (v24) has not yet become faith in the resurrection-power standing before her. The Evangelist does not condemn her hesitation; it underlines the humanness of faith. It also ensures that the subsequent miracle cannot be dismissed as premature — four days of decomposition is beyond any natural recovery.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A revelation of God: "Did I not tell you that if you believe, you will see the glory of God?" The Johannine epistemology is stated again: faith precedes and enables the vision of divine glory; sight alone does not produce faith (2:23–25; 4:48). Those who believe will see what those who demand to see before they believe cannot receive. The glory of God — which the Evangelist announced was disclosed in the signs (2:11) — is about to be disclosed in the most direct way yet. But belief is the condition of seeing it.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A revelation of God: "Father, I thank you that you have heard me." The prayer before the miracle is not a request but a thanksgiving — the Father has already heard, already answered, already aligned with the Son\'s purpose. The prayer format (thanking rather than asking) reveals the perfect unity of Father and Son: there is no gap between the Son\'s will and the Father\'s answer. The Evangelist shows that the miracle is not a moment of divine decision but the execution of a decision already made in the perfect relationship of the Trinity.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A revelation of God: "I knew that you always hear me, but I said this for the benefit of the people standing here, that they may believe that you sent me." The prayer is pedagogical — spoken aloud for the witnesses, not necessary for the Son\'s communion with the Father. The Evangelist reveals Christ\'s consistent orientation: even in the most intimate moment, he is thinking of those around him and their faith. Every word and act is oriented toward the Father\'s mission of drawing people to belief in the Son.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A direct revelation: "Lazarus, come out!" — the creative command spoken in a loud voice at the sealed tomb. The Evangelist chooses the same verb register as the divine commands of Genesis 1: "Let there be light." Here: "Come out." The word of Christ does not describe or request or invite; it creates. Ezekiel 37:9–10 is enacted: "Come, breath, from the four winds... and breathe into these slain, that they may live." The valley of dry bones comes to life; the tomb releases its occupant. The command names Lazarus specifically — the general resurrection of the last day (5:28) is here anticipated in one particular man.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A direct revelation: "The dead man came out, his hands and feet wrapped with strips of linen, and a cloth around his face." The burial wrappings confirm the reality of the death and the physical nature of the resurrection. Lazarus is the same man who died — in the same body, in the grave clothes of burial. Christ\'s resurrection, by contrast, will leave the grave clothes folded and empty (20:6–7), because he is raised to an indestructible body, not merely restored to mortal life. Lazarus\'s raising is a preview and a type; Christ\'s resurrection is the reality of which Lazarus\'s is the shadow.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A revelation of God: "many of the Jews who had come to visit Mary, and had seen what Jesus did, believed in him." The sign produces faith — the goal that the Evangelist has named throughout (20:30–31). The witnesses who followed Mary to the tomb intending only to mourn are now the recipients of the revelation they did not come to receive. The grace of God disrupts the ordinary agenda with extraordinary disclosure.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A theme: some go to the Pharisees and report what Jesus had done. The two responses to the sign — belief (v45) and report to the authorities (v46) — map the two responses to Christ throughout the Gospel. The same act of divine grace divides those who receive it from those who resist it. The report is factual — they are not lying about what happened — but the intent is opposition. The greatest sign the Evangelist narrates triggers both the greatest expression of faith and the final decision to kill Jesus.</p>',
    "47": '<p>A revelation of God: "Here is this man performing many signs." The Sanhedrin\'s own description of Jesus — "performing many signs" — is the Evangelist\'s testimony placed on the lips of his opponents. They acknowledge the reality of the signs. Their problem is not the evidence but the implications. The very thing that should lead them to faith (the signs testifying to the Father\'s mission, 5:36) is the thing that triggers their political calculation. The evidence for Christ is admitted by those who are deciding to kill him.</p>',
    "48": '<p>A theme: "If we let him go on like this, everyone will believe in him, and then the Romans will come and take away both our temple and our nation." The leaders\' fear is a political calculation about power-preservation. The irony the Evangelist constructs is double: the temple will be destroyed in 70 AD — not because of Jesus but because of Israel\'s rejection of him; and the nation will be preserved not through political management but through the death of the one they are planning to kill. They are trying to prevent the very consequences their decision will produce.</p>',
    "49": '<p>A revelation of God: "You know nothing at all!" — Caiaphas\'s rebuke of his colleagues introduces the speech that will function as unconscious prophecy. The high priest who dismisses others\' thinking speaks the most theologically significant words in the chapter. The Evangelist\'s irony is at its sharpest here: the one who says "you know nothing" is about to say more than he knows. The arrogant dismissal precedes the prophetic speech — the human contempt is the vessel through which divine speech arrives.</p>',
    "50": '<p>A shadow and direct: "it is better for you that one man die for the people than that the whole nation perish." Caiaphas intends this as political expediency — a calculation about sacrificing one to save many. The Evangelist hears in it the substitutionary logic that governs the atonement: Christ dies for the people, bearing what would otherwise fall on them. The formula "one for many" is the structure of Isaiah 53:12 ("he bore the sin of many") and Leviticus 16 (the scapegoat bearing the community\'s sin). The high priest who should understand the Day of Atonement speaks its logic about Jesus without understanding what he is saying.</p>',
    "51": '<p>A direct fulfillment: "He did not say this on his own, but as high priest that year he prophesied that Jesus would die for the Jewish nation." The Evangelist explicitly marks Caiaphas\'s words as prophecy — an utterance beyond his own intention, shaped by his office as high priest. Daniel 9:25–26 stands behind this: the Anointed One cut off for the people, the atoning death foretold. The high priest\'s office was to make atonement for Israel; Caiaphas, in condemning Jesus to death, is, without knowing it, arranging the final and complete Day of Atonement.</p>',
    "52": '<p>A direct revelation: "not only for that nation but also for the scattered children of God, to bring them together and make them one." The Evangelist extends Caiaphas\'s prophecy beyond its political frame to the universal scope of the atonement. The "scattered children of God" echoes Isaiah 49:6 (the Servant as "a light for the Gentiles, that my salvation may reach to the ends of the earth") and Ezekiel 34:12–16 (God gathering his scattered sheep from every place). The death Jesus is being condemned to will accomplish the gathering of all God\'s people from every nation into one — the one body of Christ described in Ephesians 2:11–22.</p>',
    "53": '<p>A revelation of God: "So from that day on they plotted to take his life." The decision that will lead to the cross is made in response to the sign that is most clearly a preview of the resurrection. The irony is the deepest in the Gospel: those who plot death in response to the sign of resurrection will produce the death that becomes the resurrection. The Sanhedrin\'s decision is simultaneously the most evil human act in the Gospel and the necessary precondition for the redemption the Gospel announces.</p>',
    "54": '<p>A revelation of God: Jesus withdraws to Ephraim near the wilderness. The withdrawal is not flight but patient waiting for the Father\'s timing — the same divine timing that governed his delay in coming to Lazarus (v6). The hour of the cross has been set before the world was made (17:24; Rev 13:8); no human plot can advance or delay it. He waits at the edge of the wilderness — as Israel once waited in the wilderness before entering the land — until the appointed time of the Passover.</p>',
    "55": '<p>A shadow: "When it was almost time for the Jewish Passover" — the Passover festival is the Evangelist\'s constant temporal frame for the passion (2:13; 6:4; 13:1; 18:39; 19:14). The pilgrims gathering in Jerusalem for the ceremony of the lamb\'s blood are being gathered for the Passover that ends all Passovers — the sacrifice of the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world (1:29). Every Passover since Exodus has been a shadow of this one; this one will be the substance.</p>',
    "56": '<p>A revelation of God: "Isn\'t he coming to the festival at all?" — the pilgrims\' question about Jesus is the question the Gospel has been asking since 1:11: will the one who came to his own be received? The festival crowd\'s wondering is the wondering of those at the edge of the final disclosure. The answer will be yes — he is coming to the festival, as the Lamb. He will be present at the Passover not as a pilgrim but as the sacrifice.</p>',
    "57": '<p>A theme: "the chief priests and the Pharisees had given orders that anyone who found out where Jesus was should report it." The human machinery of opposition — surveillance, informants, orders for arrest — is set in motion. This is the machinery that will be used by Judas (13:2, 21–30) to hand Jesus over. The Evangelist presents the opposition\'s preparation alongside the Passover preparation (v55) — two different kinds of preparation for the same event, one plotting death and one anticipating the sacrifice, both serving the same divine purpose without knowing it.</p>'
  }
}

